{"parse":{"title":"Bruce Bagemihl","pageid":9732220,"revid":854636845,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Bruce Bagemihl</b> is a <a href=\"/wiki/Canadians\" title=\"Canadians\">Canadian</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Biologist\" title=\"Biologist\">biologist</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Linguist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Linguist\">linguist</a>, and author of the book <i>Biological Exuberance: <a href=\"/wiki/Animal_Homosexuality\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Animal Homosexuality\">Animal Homosexuality</a> and Natural Diversity</i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-mcdonald2006_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-mcdonald2006-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-fletcher2007_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-fletcher2007-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Life_and_career\">Life and career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bruce_Bagemihl&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Life and career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>He served on the faculty of <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_British_Columbia\" title=\"University of British Columbia\">University of British Columbia</a>, where he taught linguistics and cognitive science,<sup id=\"cite_ref-catdir.loc_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-catdir.loc-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> and earned a Ph.D. in linguistics from there in 1988.\n</p><p><i>Biological Exuberance</i> cites numerous studies on more than 450 species (see <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_animals_displaying_homosexual_behavior\" title=\"List of animals displaying homosexual behavior\">List of animals displaying homosexual behavior</a>) showing that <a href=\"/wiki/Homosexual\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Homosexual\">homosexual</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Bisexual\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Bisexual\">bisexual</a> behaviors are common among animals and proposes a theory of sexual behavior in which <a href=\"/wiki/Reproduction\" title=\"Reproduction\">reproduction</a> is only one of its principal biological functions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Harrold1999_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Harrold1999-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Bagemihl proposes that group cohesion and lessening of tensions, seen for example among <a href=\"/wiki/Bonobo\" title=\"Bonobo\">bonobos</a>, are other important functions of sexual behavior.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Kluger1999_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kluger1999-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>  He also argues that the implications for humans of homosexual behaviour across the animal kingdom are \"enormous.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Harrold1999_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Harrold1999-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Kluger1999_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Kluger1999-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>His book on homosexuality in animals was cited by the <a href=\"/wiki/American_Psychiatric_Association\" title=\"American Psychiatric Association\">American Psychiatric Association</a> and other groups in their <i><a href=\"/wiki/Amici_curiae\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Amici curiae\">amici curiae</a></i> brief to the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Supreme_Court\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"United States Supreme Court\">United States Supreme Court</a> in <i><a href=\"/wiki/Lawrence_v._Texas\" title=\"Lawrence v. Texas\">Lawrence v. Texas</a></i>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> the case which ultimately struck down <a href=\"/wiki/Sodomy_laws\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sodomy laws\">sodomy laws</a> across the United States.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Love_That_Dare_Not_Squeak_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Love_That_Dare_Not_Squeak-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The book formed the basis for the museum exhibition <a href=\"/wiki/Against_Nature%3F\" title=\"Against Nature?\">Against Nature?</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Love_That_Dare_Not_Squeak_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Love_That_Dare_Not_Squeak-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>He has also published several essays and scientific articles on issues related to language, biology, gender, and sexuality.<sup id=\"cite_ref-catdir.loc_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-catdir.loc-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Bruce_Bagemihl&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-mcdonald2006-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-mcdonald2006_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">McDonald, Maggie (January 4, 2006). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg18925332.200-biological-exuberance-by-bruce-bagemihl.html\">\"Biological Exuberance by Bruce Bagemihl\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/New_Scientist\" title=\"New Scientist\">New Scientist</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">March 10,</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=New+Scientist&amp;rft.atitle=Biological+Exuberance+by+Bruce+Bagemihl&amp;rft.date=2006-01-04&amp;rft.aulast=McDonald&amp;rft.aufirst=Maggie&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.newscientist.com%2Farticle%2Fmg18925332.200-biological-exuberance-by-bruce-bagemihl.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-fletcher2007-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-fletcher2007_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Fletcher, Martin (January 3, 2007). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20070217061246/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1288633.ece\">\"Birds do it, bees do it ...\"</a> <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Times\" title=\"The Times\">The Times</a></i>. Archived from <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article1288633.ece\">the original</a> on February 17, 2007.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Times&amp;rft.atitle=Birds+do+it%2C+bees+do+it+...&amp;rft.date=2007-01-03&amp;rft.aulast=Fletcher&amp;rft.aufirst=Martin&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.timesonline.co.uk%2Ftol%2Flife_and_style%2Farticle1288633.ece&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-catdir.loc-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-catdir.loc_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-catdir.loc_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://catdir.loc.gov/catdir/bios/hol054/98028528.html\">\"Publisher-supplied biographical information about contributor(s) for Biological exuberance&#160;: animal homosexuality and natural diversity / Bruce Bagemihl&#160;; illustrated by John Megahan\"</a>. <i>catdir.loc.gov</i>. Library of Congress<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">18 September</span> 2017</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.jtitle=catdir.loc.gov&amp;rft.atitle=Publisher-supplied+biographical+information+about+contributor%28s%29+for+Biological+exuberance+%3A+animal+homosexuality+and+natural+diversity+%2F+Bruce+Bagemihl+%3B+illustrated+by+John+Megahan&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcatdir.loc.gov%2Fcatdir%2Fbios%2Fhol054%2F98028528.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Harrold1999-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Harrold1999_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Harrold1999_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Harrold, Max (February 16, 1999). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aGMEAAAAMBAJ&amp;pg=PA61\">\"Creature Comforts\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Advocate\" title=\"The Advocate\">The Advocate</a></i> (779). <a href=\"/wiki/Here_Publishing\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Here Publishing\">Here Publishing</a>. pp.&#160;61\u201362<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">March 10,</span> 2018</span>. <q>In his news book, <i>Biological Exuberance: Animal Homosexuality and Natural Diversity</i> ... author Bruce Bagemihl portrays an animal kingdom that embraces a whole spectrum of sexual orientations ... [and] a complex mosaic that resembles humanity ... 'It's an expanded vision of what the natural world is all about,' [Bagemihl] says.  'We're not alone in having a range of sexual behaviours.  This is something that is all-encompassing.' ... At 751 pages and with photos and documentation of homosexual behaviour in more than 450 species of mammals, birds, repties, and insects, <i>Biological Exuberance</i> brings the dusty facts to light as Bagemihl deconstructs the all-heterosexual Noah's Ark we've been sold.  ...  Although he doesn't claim to know the motivations of animals, Bagemihl says he does know procreation is not always the driving force: 'Same-sex couplings occur in the presence of the opposite sex, and in and out of captivity, and in and out of mating season.'</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Advocate&amp;rft.atitle=Creature+Comforts&amp;rft.issue=779&amp;rft.pages=61-62&amp;rft.date=1999-02-16&amp;rft.aulast=Harrold&amp;rft.aufirst=Max&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com.au%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DaGMEAAAAMBAJ%26pg%3DPA61&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Kluger1999-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kluger1999_5-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Kluger1999_5-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a href=\"/wiki/Jeffrey_Kluger\" title=\"Jeffrey Kluger\">Kluger, Jeffrey</a> (April 26, 1999). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,990813,00.html\">\"The Gay Side of Nature\"</a>. <i><a href=\"/wiki/Time_(magazine)\" title=\"Time (magazine)\">Time</a></i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">March 10,</span> 2018</span>. <q>Although gay himself, Bagemihl says he did not write his landmark book (which he spent nine years researching) simply because of his own sexual identity but rather because 'the implications for humans are enormous.'</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Time&amp;rft.atitle=The+Gay+Side+of+Nature&amp;rft.date=1999-04-26&amp;rft.aulast=Kluger&amp;rft.aufirst=Jeffrey&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.time.com%2Ftime%2Fmagazine%2Farticle%2F0%2C9171%2C990813%2C00.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a href=\"/wiki/American_Psychological_Association\" title=\"American Psychological Association\">American Psychological Association</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/American_Psychiatric_Association\" title=\"American Psychiatric Association\">American Psychiatric Association</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/National_Association_of_Social_Workers\" title=\"National Association of Social Workers\">National Association of Social Workers</a>; <a href=\"/wiki/National_Association_of_Social_Workers#Chapters\" title=\"National Association of Social Workers\">Texas Chapter of the National Association of Social Workers</a> (January 2003). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.apa.org/about/offices/ogc/amicus/lawrence.pdf\">\"Brief for Amici Curiae in Support of Petitioners in the case of <i>John Geddes Lawrence and Tyron Garner v. State of Texas</i>\"</a> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(PDF)</span><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">March 10,</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Brief+for+Amici+Curiae+in+Support+of+Petitioners+in+the+case+of+John+Geddes+Lawrence+and+Tyron+Garner+v.+State+of+Texas&amp;rft.date=2003-01&amp;rft.au=American+Psychological+Association&amp;rft.au=American+Psychiatric+Association&amp;rft.au=National+Association+of+Social+Workers&amp;rft.au=Texas+Chapter+of+the+National+Association+of+Social+Workers&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.apa.org%2Fabout%2Foffices%2Fogc%2Famicus%2Flawrence.pdf&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ABruce+Bagemihl\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_n